The first virtual provider is already coming to Czechia this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite well equipped, and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be allowed to wait any longer.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers are working at the most expensive in Europe is often reported on mobile.cz.
This was confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradox situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradox, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration of far more than 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to see that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) is often obliged to assist Pavel Dvořák, who in the past often expressed that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network no longer has many opportunities (by the way, it would probably not even find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market led to a significant price reduction, which the traditional mobile phone providers had to react to.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile there were similar voices on the market in the United Kingdom as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
Besides, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is Penta's financial group, which has U:fon, among other things, in the Czech Republic.
The benefit of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually seen as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, however often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least half cheaper SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to set a non-climate target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could occur in Poland as well as in the Czech Republic.
It also doubts the press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepýk: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is moderated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile phone providers
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It will come rather to a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says Jana Studnikková, spokesperson for the Penta Group of Finance.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not only entitled to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Its interest at the start of a virtual mobile provider has long been shown by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed networks, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we were able to make progress in the negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times come now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this point, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has great specifications in relation to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň, in his statement on Mobil.cz from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds, in rare accordance with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobiles, hardly a virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this point, we had to have a specific offer to think in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepýký says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we see from the customer's perspective as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to seek a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
Responsibilities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The mobile provider's behaviour is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, which would lead to lowering prices and thus also to a fall in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made market entry easier?
The fact that the providers can draw on a string when it comes to something also indicates the long time and time for the creation of U:fon.
The most powerful pressure in the direction of ČTÚ went to the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
Now, however, U:fon is only suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile radio market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and in particular on his services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
But this related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers," according to our request Kristian Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
The representatives of the supplier would not be surprised by such a formulation.
From an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position on the market, this is more than worrying.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual providers normally work, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction does not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the almost already moving harmony of the three mobile operators is derived from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is at hand.
Just as the absolute same fuel price at the tanks is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a hard competition struggle.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter which indicate any action directed against competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way on the matter.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so neither does he have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening the mobile phone market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the ČTÚ, since telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that he is necessarily taking a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators will be acting in a similar manner.
Complaints from a number of stakeholders (including the company GTS Novera mentioned above) are evidenced by the very similar obstacles encountered in negotiations with all suppliers.
The abolition of responsibility for ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, which distances the ÚOHS from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to implement the recently adopted telecommunications bill's novelty to extend CTU's competence in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this very well, but they probably have different interests.
It's okay if no one's looking.
The operation of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are also several in the Czech mobile networks, remains disregarded.
There are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
This is usually the case for companies operating in the area of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile telephone services provide, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to be a classic company company that orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar type of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then be engaged, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the company concerned," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
It is quite unlikely, however, that such a thing does not happen to the operators of mobile phones.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such action.
These companies do not pay too much attention to the activities of the companies, while at the same time, unlike actual virtual suppliers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepýk points out some problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a very low percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run in their phone name, so they cannot have complete access to it as the normal customers of mobile phone providers."
However, this was to be at least unusual for the CTU.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile service providers close their eyes before such a move, why do they block a virtual service provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has very strong competence to detect such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to satisfy itself with the supplier's statement, they knew nothing about it and their business conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As already emphasized in the text several times, the market entry of the virtual provider brought a significant drop in prices for the various services.
In this way, virtually all countries where virtual providers have been created have tried to prevent their origins from being virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a small, or very strong market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, at this moment, regulatory bodies are involved, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and further followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot give the impression that uncertainty in the skills in these cases is more than favorable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile phone market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interests (to discriminate).
And then the Czechs will finally no longer call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
