The psychology of the area - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error offering.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people in a competition, such as a rise in eBay, do not get beat and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto, while the others participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the samplers were investigated through functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to earn money, however, an increased activity of the Strait, a complex below the brain, was measured at the loss of the auction, where the opponent's overlap played a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the increase in prices could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the space.
In order to undermine their thesis, the economists in the research group have also employed research to track the money.
In this case, three groups against a partner should be provided under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and then made their interventions.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they came out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis was on one on winning, while on the other on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against loss" group were willing to use higher positions than those in the control or profit group.
"These results cannot be derived from any earlier economic theory.
These are the behaviours observed in auctions so far only based on the joy of winning, or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories was solved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we have now prepared a third statement" - said Andrew Scotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you talk to your doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
However, the number of infected people is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which means that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for hepatitis caused by various viruses, infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common; however, the errors and diseases differ.
As a result, hepatitis A and E are distributed in two different species: in hepatitis A and E by the digestion tract (for example, by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretion or mirror).
Travellers are recommended for vaccination against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal pain and fractures.
Then the yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the healing can take up to two or three weeks.
Around the world, about 1 million people die every year from the more severe diseases of hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and liver cirrosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only every ten infected person is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected don't even know about their disease, since the errant destroys the liver cells at home - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, time-consuming precautions, such as regular checks, are essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more frequent: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
The number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is currently estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory study, it is advisable to consult the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In due course, the disease can be healed, the virus can be eradicated, thereby preventing the risk of infection and presenting cancer.
The World Day of Hepatitis is held on September 30th, 2004, for the first time on patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their formation and the importance of early recognition.
