What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if we did not imitate nature's barrier sensors?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln to create new preventable systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic system controlled by Autoboters of the type BR23C, a mini-auto, equipped with the properties of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology-PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bees, which can see in any direction and in an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to reflect the function of the compound eye, the researchers come up with the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in an area of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in second break parts, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this manoeuvre is purely instinctive.
"If not, the autobot could not react quickly enough to remove the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the autobot project.
The system needs to react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the lowest and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is still inevitable within the accident.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees if they deviate from other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the deviation, unlike the bees, can not go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and it can only be in the direction of the turnability of the tires.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are easier and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained, it comes to the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device must process only some inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It doesn't have to store these, or by using earlier maneuvers to produce an intuitive, logical reaction, so it takes on a hand full KB memory.
There's no need for gigabyte and megabyte-hard memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which will be serialized in production after Nissan's assessment within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology at GPS satellite navigation, by raising the driver’s awareness of obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
